entry.title: [DTC] Mark different timing points for tab strip transition
entry.content:
The design of TabStripTransitionCoordinator#getTabStripHeight returns a fixed height representing the expected height after the tab strip transition. To external classes that depends on the tab strip height for offset / dimension calculation, the values can be wrong during the transition phase.



Because mToolbar.getTabStripHeight() can return the height of the end state of the transition, it can be inconsistent with the actual size - ToolbarLayout's top margin at the first frame of the transition, and result in a wrong calculated size for the shadow within ToolbarControlContainer. To fix, when capture the top toolbar UI resource, this CL use the height from the toolbar shadow directly instead of calculating based on toolbar / tab strip height.



This CL also changes the expectations for ToolbarManager#getTabStripHeightSupplier and Toolbar#getTabStripHeight. The former now always represent the end-state of the transition, while the latter represent the space reserved for the strip on top of the toolbar. With such, Toolbar#getTabStripHeight should have limited usage besides the classes involved in tab strip transition. Changing the API's visibility will be addressed in a follow up.



Demo: https://drive.google.com/file/d/16mSnhU8uJZDaUekm612hTA3NF6CM6WXh/view?usp=drive_link&resourcekey=0-CNIxB3e52-2hfFNwz8yqOg

entry.title: mojo-js: Remove WebUIJsBridge implementation
entry.content:
There was a fundamental design flaw in this approach that made it not

a good fit for important WebUI use cases.



Essentially, centralizing all interface binders into one interface,

WebUIJsBridge, broke standalone JS libraries implemented on top of Mojo.

These libraries rely on the fact that there's a bind function exposed

on `window` i.e. `Mojo.bindInterface()` that libraries can use to bind

needed interfaces.



Exposing interfaces through WebUIJsBridge isn't compatible with this

pattern as standalone libraries don't have access to the WebUIJsBridge

bindings.



We could build extra infra to support these types of libraries, but

that would further increase the complexity of an already complex system.



For this reason, the WebUI team is looking at other less complex

alternatives that would fit with this model of standalone libraries.



Fixed: 1407936

entry.title: Fix crash when TabDragController is destroyed during Init.
entry.content:
TabDragController may be destroyed during Init when it calls SetCapture. This is because the OS calls to take capture may reenter Chrome, and tab dragging may end during those reentrant calls.



This CL fixes the immediate crash, which happens when TabDragController is dereferenced after Init to do some logging. https://crbug.com/1509581 tracks followup work to extend this approach across the rest of TabDragController.



I also moved SetCapture to the end of Init again, and added a giant 'do not add code below here' warning. The code that was after SetCapture wouldn't have run before we potentially reentered TabDragController - so basically TDC was partially uninitialized during that period.

entry.title: [ios] Fix overscroll actions animation
entry.content:
The animation that happens as the overscroll actions view is going away

appeared to be especially abrupt and glitchy on the NTP. After some

investigation, it appears that the "header inset" (the content offset

in the parent ScrollView where the overscroll view is placed) was being

used incorrectly in this animation. On the NTP, the top of the parent

ScrollView's content is not offset zero, it is somewhere in the

neighborhood of -550px because the top of the feed is always offset

zero. This is wildly different than a "normal" WebKit view and resulted

in a very short glitchy animation.



In both the NTP and WebKit view cases, the added offset was causing the

animation to not really complete. For example, as the offset nears zero

the reload icon should rotate CCW as it disappears and the New Tab and

Close icons slide towards the center. This part of the animation was

lost (completely on the NTP, partially on WebKit views) because of the

offset and it really just slid up off screen and faded out. This offset

may have been added with the introduction of the notched iPhone which

resulted in an additional offset at the top of the screen.



Additionally, the parent view was not animating its slide back up into

position as it appeared the code was trying to do. This was fixed by

changing the setContentOffset:animated: to instead use a UIView

animation which included both the contentOffset and the contentInset,

resulting in a smooth slide back up into position.



Existing animation:

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1miStOXWKHbALJP8-00KnZbtzJhL5PQiT/view?usp=sharing



Fixed animation:

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1KIv_Y0rwEl0UGRxrZrwzscKvnAu6fC36/view?usp=sharing



Fixed: 1502218

entry.title: Allow OpenXr Hand Trackers to be controllers
entry.content:
Provides infrastructure to allow OpenXrHandTracker type objects to

provide the necessary information to surface a controller based on

the tracked hands, in the event that the OpenXr system does not return

any controller for the specified hand. Also provides implementation

instructions on how to do so. If we want to have a given HandTracker

override any interaction profile bindings, we could update the logic

(probably with the addition of another bool on OpenXrHandController)

in OpenXrController::UpdateInteractionProfile.



Primary intended implementation is for children to extend both

`OpenXrHandTracker` and `OpenXrHandController` and then to

override `OpenXrHandTracker::controller()` to return `this`, but did not

want to enforce any guarantees implied by that onto children.

entry.title: [Extensions UserScripts] Take host permissions into account in tracker
entry.content:
An extension can register a script with broader patterns than the host

permissions it requested access to. For example, registering a script

for but extension only having access to a.example and

b.example.



Therefore, ScriptInjectionTracker should take these permissions into

account when calculating if a script will inject. Otherwise, the set of renderers we mark as having injected scripts will be broader than it should be (we'll think extensions injected in renderers they haven't yet).



This also includes notifying the ScriptInjectionTracker when host

permissions updates happen, so it can update its list.

entry.title: [OBC] Add support for domain cookies when loading/inserting cookies.
entry.content:
This CL adds proper support for loading and inserting "domain cookies."

In the context of origin-bound cookies "domain cookies" are those which

specified the "Domain" attribute and thus are accessible by sub-domains.



Domain cookies are treated slightly differently in OBC in that their

port value is ignored, meaning that domain cookies can be set by or sent

to any port.



CanonicalCookie changes:

* The concept of a UniqueDomainKey was added which optionally includes

the source_scheme of a cookie. This is different from the existing

UniqueKey which, optionally, includes both the source_scheme and

source_port.

* IsEquivalent() was changed to use the UniqueDomainKey when comparing

a domain cookie.



CookieMonster changes:

* TrimDuplicateCookiesForKey() was modified to specifically look for

domain cookies and check for duplicates using the UniqueDomainKey.

Just like its existing functionality it sorts based on creation date

and deletes all but the most recently created.

* The changes to CanonicalCookie means that

MaybeDeleteEquivalentCookieAndUpdateStatus() gets the correct behavior

"for free".

allocation uses media/gpu/chromeos/platform_video_frame_utils), so

Only issue is on Qualcomm SC7180 (trogdor) where minigbm always

code sets --disable-buffer-bw-compression, which Ozone in turn uses

to set an environment variable for minigbm to disable that behaviour.

This flag-to-environment-var doesn't need to be in Ozone at all since

it's just used for testing; as a matter of fact the flag is not

really needed since test code can set the environment variable

directly: this CL does that, effectively removing the flag.



(*) This will be changed by hnt@ via trying to allocate with modifiers

explicitly stated, for Intel Media Compression; in time we should

do the same for QC and this flag/environment variable won't be needed.

entry.content:

fixing the failing test.

entry.content:
Creates a pref to differentiate between implicit/explicit sign ins.
